#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:46
#, no-wrap
msgid "System service commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:49
msgid ""
"`firewalld` is run as a service on your machine. It starts when the machine "
"does, or it should. If for some reason `firewalld` is not already enabled on "
"your machine, you can do that with a simple command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "systemctl enable --now firewalld\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:55
msgid ""
"The `--now` flag starts the service as soon as its enabled, and let's you "
"skip the `systemctl start firewalld` step."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:57
msgid ""
"As with all services on Rocky Linux, you can check if the firewall is "
"running with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "systemctl status firewalld\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:63
msgid "To stop it altogether:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "systemctl stop firewalld\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:69
msgid "And to give the service a hard restart:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic `firewalld` configuration and management commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:77
msgid ""
"`firewalld` is configured with the `firewall-cmd` command. You can, for "
"example, check the status of `firewalld` with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --state\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:83
msgid ""
"After every *permanent* change to your firewall, you'll need to reload it to "
"see the changes. You can give the firewall configurations a \"soft restart\" "
"with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If you reload your configurations that haven't been made permanent, they'll disappear on you.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:93
msgid "You can see all of your configurations and settings at once with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --list-all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:99
msgid "That command will output something that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"public (active)\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces: enp9s0\n"
"  sources:\n"
"  services: ssh\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:117
#, no-wrap
msgid "Saving your changes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:120
msgid "!!! Warning \"Warning: Seriously, read this next bit.\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "    By default, all changes to `firewalld`'s configuration are temporary. If you restart the whole `firewalld` service, or restart your machine, none of your changes to the firewall will be saved unless you do one of two very specific things.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:124
msgid ""
"It's best practice to test all of your changes one by one, reloading your "
"firewall config as you go. That way, if you accidentally lock yourself out "
"of anything, you can restart the service (or the machine), all of those "
"changes disappear as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:126
msgid ""
"But once you have a working configuration, you can save your changes "
"permanently with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --runtime-to-permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:132
msgid ""
"However, if you're absolutely sure about what you're doing, and just want to "
"add the rule and move on with your life, you can add the `--permanent` flag "
"to any configuration command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:133
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --permanent [the rest of your command]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "Managing Zones"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:140
msgid ""
"Before anything else, I need to explain zones. Zones are a feature that "
"basically allow you to define different sets of rules for different "
"situations. Zones are a huge part of `firewalld` so it pays to understand "
"how they work."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:142
msgid ""
"If your machine has multiple ways to connect to different networks (eg. "
"Ethernet and WiFi), you can decide that one connection is more trusted than "
"the other. You might set your Ethernet connection to the \"trusted\" zone if "
"it's only connected to a local network that you built, and put the WiFi "
"(which might be connected to the internet) in the \"public\" zone with more "
"stringent restrictions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:146
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld.md:157
#, no-wrap
msgid "    A zone can *only* be in an active state if it has one of these two conditions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    1. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:149
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld.md:160
msgid "The zone is assigned to a network interface"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    2. '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:149
msgid "The zone is assigned source IPs or network ranges. (More on that below)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:151
msgid ""
"Default zones include the following (I've taken this explanation from "
"[DigitalOcean's guide to `firewalld`](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/"
"tutorials/how-to-set-up-a-firewall-using-firewalld-on-centos-8), which you "
"should also read):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:153
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **drop:** The lowest level of trust. All incoming connections are dropped without reply and only outgoing connections are possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:155
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **block:** Similar to the above, but instead of simply dropping connections, incoming requests are rejected with an icmp-host-prohibited or icmp6-adm-prohibited message.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:157
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **public:** Represents public, untrusted networks. You donâ€™t trust other computers but may allow selected incoming connections on a case-by-case basis.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:159
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **external:** External networks in the event that you are using the firewall as your gateway. It is configured for NAT masquerading so that your internal network remains private but reachable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:161
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **internal:** The other side of the external zone, used for the internal portion of a gateway. The computers are fairly trustworthy and some additional services are available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **dmz:** Used for computers located in a DMZ (isolated computers that will not have access to the rest of your network). Only certain incoming connections are allowed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:165
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **work:** Used for work machines. Trust most of the computers in the network. A few more services might be allowed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:167
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **home:** A home environment. It generally implies that you trust most of the other computers and that a few more services will be accepted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:169
#, no-wrap
msgid "> **trusted:** Trust all of the machines in the network. The most open of the available options and should be used sparingly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:171
msgid ""
"Okay, so some of those explanations get complicated, but Honestly? The "
"average beginner can get by with understanding \"trusted\", \"home\", and "
"\"public\", and when to use which."
msgstr ""

