#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:253
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-port=9001/tcp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:260
#, no-wrap
msgid "    About that `/tcp` bit:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:262
#, no-wrap
msgid "    That `/tcp` bit at the end tells the firewall that connections will be coming in over the Transfer Control Protocol, which is what you'll be using for most server-and-home-related stuff.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:264
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Alternatives like UDP are for debugging, or other very specific kinds of stuff that frankly aren't in the scope of this guide. Refer to the documentation of whatever app or service you specifically want to open up a port for.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:266
msgid "To remove a port, just reverse the command with a single word change:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-port=9001/tcp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:271
#, no-wrap
msgid "Managing Services"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:274
msgid ""
"Services, as you might imagine, are fairly standardized programs that run on "
"your computer. `firewalld` is set up so that it can just open the way for "
"most common services whenever you need to do that."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:276
msgid ""
"This is the preferred way to open up the ports for these common services, "
"and a whole lot more:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:281
msgid "HTTP and HTTPS: for web servers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:281
msgid "FTP: For moving files back and forth (the old fashioned way)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:281
msgid ""
"SSH: For controlling remote machines and moving files back and forth the new "
"way"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:281
msgid "Samba: For sharing files with Windows machines"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:285
#, no-wrap
msgid "    **Never remove the SSH service from a remote server's firewall!**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:287
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Remember, SSH is what you use to log in to your server. Unless you have another way to access the physical server, or its shell (ie via. a control panel provided by the host), removing the SSH service will lock you out permanently.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:289
#, no-wrap
msgid "    You'll either need to contact support to get your access back, or reinstall the OS entirely.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:290
#, no-wrap
msgid "Service management commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:293
msgid ""
"To see a list of all available service services that you could potentially "
"add to your firewall, run:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:294
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --get-services\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:299
msgid "To see what services you currently have active on your firewall, use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --list-services\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:305
msgid ""
"To open up a service in your firewall (eg. HTTP in the public zone), use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:306
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service=http\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:311
msgid "To remove/close a service on your firewall, just change one word again:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:312
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=http\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:317
msgid "!!! Note \"Note: You can add your own services\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:319
#, no-wrap
msgid "    And customize the heck out of them, too. However, that's a topic that gets kind of complex. Get familiar with `firewalld` first, and go from there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:320
#, no-wrap
msgid "Restricting Access"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:323
msgid ""
"Let's say you have a server, and you just don't want to make it public. if "
"you want to define just who is allowed to access it via SSH, or view some "
"private web pages/apps, you can do that."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:325
msgid ""
"There are a couple of methods to accomplish this. First, for a more locked-"
"down server, you can pick one of the more restrictive zones, assign your "
"network device to it, add the SSH service to it as shown above, and then "
"whitelist your own public IP address like so:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=trusted --add-source=192.168.1.0 [< insert your IP here]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:331
msgid ""
"You can make it a range of IP addresses by adding a higher number at the end "
"like so:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:332
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=trusted --add-source=192.168.1.0/24 [< insert your IP here]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:337
msgid ""
"Again, just change `--add-source` to `--remove-source` in order to reverse "
"the process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:339
msgid ""
"However, if you're managing a remote server with a website on it that needs "
"to be public, and still only want to open up SSH for one IP address or a "
"small range of them, you have a couple of options. In both of these "
"examples, the sole network interface is assigned to the public zone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:341
msgid ""
"First, you can use a \"rich rule\" to your public zone, and it would look "
"something like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:342
#, no-wrap
msgid "# firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=public --add-rich-rule='rule family=\"ipv4\" source address=\"192.168.1.0/24\" service name=\"ssh\" accept'\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:347
msgid ""
"Once the rich rule is in place, *don't* make the rules permanent yet. First, "
"remove the SSH service from the public zone configuration, and test your "
"connection to make sure you can still access the server via SSH."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:349
msgid "Your configuration should now look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:350
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"your@server ~# firewall-cmd --list-all\n"
"public (active)\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces: wlp3s0\n"
"  sources:\n"
"  services: cockpit dhcpv6-client\n"
"  ports: 80/tcp 443/tcp\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
"        rule family=\"ipv4\" source address=\"192.168.1.0/24\" service name=\"ssh\" accept\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:371
msgid ""
"Secondly, you can use two different zones at a time. If you have your "
"interface bound to the public zone, you can activate a second zone (the "
"\"trusted\" zone for example) by adding a source IP or IP range to it as "
"shown above. Then, add the SSH service to the trusted zone, and remove it "
"from the public zone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:373
msgid "When you're done, the output should look a bit like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:374
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"your@server ~# firewall-cmd --list-all\n"
"public (active)\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces: wlp3s0\n"
"  sources:\n"
"  services: cockpit dhcpv6-client\n"
"  ports: 80/tcp 443/tcp\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
"your@server ~# firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=trusted\n"
"trusted (active)\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces:\n"
"  sources: 192.168.0.0/24\n"
"  services: ssh\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:408
msgid ""
"If you get locked out, restart the server (most VPS control panels have an "
"option for this) and try again."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:412
#, no-wrap
msgid "    These techniques only work if you have a static IP address.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:414
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If you're stuck with an internet service provider that changes your IP address every time your modem reboots, don't use these rules (at least not for SSH) until you have a fix for that. You'll lock yourself out of your server\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:416
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Either upgrade your internet plan/provider, or get a VPN that provides you with a dedicated IP, and *never, ever* lose it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "    In the meantime, [install and configure fail2ban](https://wiki.crowncloud.net/?How_to_Install_Fail2Ban_on_RockyLinux_8), which can help cut down on brute force attacks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:420
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Obviously, on a local network that you control (and where you can set every machine's IP address manually), you can use all of these rules as much as you like.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:421
#, no-wrap
msgid "Final Notes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:424
msgid ""
"This is far from an exhaustive guide, and you can learn a whole lot more "
"with the [official `firewalld` documentation](https://firewalld.org/"
"documentation/). There are also handy app-specific guides all over the "
"internet that will show you how to set up your firewall for for those "
"specific apps."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:426
#, no-wrap
msgid "For you fans of `iptables` (if you've gotten this far...), [we have a guide](firewalld.md) detailing some of the differences in how `firewalld` and `iptables` work. That guide might help you figure out if you want to stay with `firewalld` or go back to The Old Ways<sup>(TM)</sup>. There is something to be said for The Old Ways<sup>(TM)</sup>, in this case.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:430
msgid ""
"And that is `firewalld` in as few words as I could manage while still "
"explaining all the basics. Take it slow, experiment carefully, and don't "
"make any rules permanent until you're sure they work."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld-beginners.md:431
msgid ""
"And, you know, have fun. Once you have the basics down, actually setting up "
"a decent, workable firewall can take 5-10 minutes."
msgstr ""
